# Mule Salesforce Connector

The Mule Salesforce connector (`mule-salesforce-connector`) supports SOAP, REST, Bulk API, Streaming API, and Composite API against any Salesforce org (Sandbox or Production).

## 1. Add Dependency

In `pom.xml`:

```xml
<dependency>
  <groupId>com.mulesoft.connectors</groupId>
  <artifactId>mule-salesforce-connector</artifactId>
  <version>11.1.0</version>
  <classifier>mule-plugin</classifier>
</dependency>
```

## 2. Global Config (in `global-configs.xml`)

Salesforce supports several auth flows. Pick ONE per org:

### Username + Password + Security Token (simplest, dev/test)
```xml
<sfdc:sfdc-config name="Salesforce_Org_config" doc:name="Salesforce Org">
  <sfdc:basic-connection
      username="${sfdc.username}"
      password="${sfdc.password}"
      securityToken="${sfdc.token}"
      url="${sfdc.url}"/>
</sfdc:sfdc-config>
```

### CRITICAL: pick the right login endpoint per org type

The agent MUST ask the user "what type of Salesforce org is this?" during init and pick the right endpoint. Wrong endpoint always returns `INVALID_LOGIN: Invalid username, password, security token` — looks like a credential issue but isn't.

| Org type | SOAP login endpoint | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| **Production** | `https://login.salesforce.com/services/Soap/u/59.0` | The "real" org |
| **Developer Edition** | `https://login.salesforce.com/services/Soap/u/59.0` | Free standalone dev org from developer.salesforce.com — uses the **production** endpoint, NOT the sandbox endpoint |
| **Sandbox** (Dev/UAT/Full) | `https://test.salesforce.com/services/Soap/u/59.0` | Forked off a Production org. Username usually has a `.sandboxname` suffix (e.g. `you@company.com.dev1`). |
| **Trailhead Playground** | `https://login.salesforce.com/services/Soap/u/59.0` | Same as Developer Edition |
| **My Domain enabled** (any) | `https://<mydomain>.my.salesforce.com/services/Soap/u/59.0` | Org-specific URL; required if Production has My Domain login enforcement |

Never hardcode the URL in `global-configs.xml` — put it in `config.yaml` as `sfdc.url` so it can change per environment without touching XML.

### OAuth JWT Bearer (recommended for prod / server-to-server)
```xml
<sfdc:sfdc-config name="Salesforce_Prod_config" doc:name="Salesforce Prod">
  <sfdc:oauth-jwt-connection
      consumerKey="${sfdc.consumerKey}"
      keyStore="keystores/sfdc.jks"
      storePassword="${sfdc.storePassword}"
      principal="${sfdc.principal}"
      audienceUrl="https://login.salesforce.com"/>
</sfdc:sfdc-config>
```

## 3. `config.yaml` Properties

```yaml
sfdc:
  username: "integration@acme.com.sandbox"
  # password and token live in env vars or secure-properties — NEVER here
```

For secrets, NEVER inline credentials in YAML/XML and NEVER use `${env.X}` in property files — Mule 4 does not auto-resolve `${env.X}` to OS environment variables. Either:

- Inject as JVM system properties at launch (e.g. `mule.bat console -M-Dsfdc.password=...`) and reference `${sfdc.password}` from `global-configs.xml`, OR
- Use an encrypted `secure-properties.yaml` (CloudHub / on-prem secure properties module).

See `mule-init-context.mdc` "CRITICAL Mule Property Resolution Gotcha" for full details.

## 4. Operations

### Insert (Create) — single record
```xml
<sfdc:create config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config" type="Account" doc:name="Create Account">
  <sfdc:records>#[[{
    Name: payload.name,
    Industry: payload.industry default "Other",
    BillingCity: payload.city
  }]]</sfdc:records>
</sfdc:create>
```
**Result shape**: see §5 — the connector returns `{ successful, items: [{ successful, id, payload: { success, id, errors }, ... }] }`. Read results from `payload.items[0]`, NOT `payload[0]`. The §7 pattern shows the correct success/error extraction.

### Insert — multiple records
```xml
<sfdc:create config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config" type="Contact" doc:name="Create Contacts">
  <sfdc:records>#[payload map { FirstName: $.firstName, LastName: $.lastName, Email: $.email, AccountId: vars.accountId }]</sfdc:records>
</sfdc:create>
```

### Upsert (insert-or-update by external Id)
```xml
<sfdc:upsert config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config"
             type="Account"
             externalIdFieldName="External_Id__c"
             doc:name="Upsert Account">
  <sfdc:records>#[[{ External_Id__c: payload.externalId, Name: payload.name }]]</sfdc:records>
</sfdc:upsert>
```

### Update — by Salesforce Id
```xml
<sfdc:update config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config" type="Account" doc:name="Update Account">
  <sfdc:records>#[[{ Id: vars.accountId, Industry: payload.industry }]]</sfdc:records>
</sfdc:update>
```

### Delete
```xml
<sfdc:delete config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config" doc:name="Delete Account">
  <sfdc:ids>#[[vars.accountId]]</sfdc:ids>
</sfdc:delete>
```

### Query (SOQL)
```xml
<sfdc:query config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config" doc:name="Query top accounts">
  <sfdc:salesforce-query>SELECT Id, Name, Industry FROM Account WHERE Industry = ':industry' LIMIT 50</sfdc:salesforce-query>
  <sfdc:parameters>#[{ industry: vars.industry }]</sfdc:parameters>
</sfdc:query>
```

### Bulk Insert (10K+ records)
```xml
<sfdc:create-bulk config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config" type="Contact" doc:name="Bulk insert Contacts">
  <sfdc:records>#[payload]</sfdc:records>
</sfdc:create-bulk>
```
Use Bulk for > ~2000 records. Returns a `jobId` you can poll with `<sfdc:get-job-info>` and `<sfdc:get-batch-result>`.

## 5. The ACTUAL response shape from `sfdc:create` / `sfdc:update` / `sfdc:upsert`

The Mule SF connector returns a **BatchOperationResult** — NOT a flat `SaveResult` array. This is the most common cause of "my success check doesn't fire" or "I get 'no errors[]' even though SF rejected the record". Verified shape:

```json
{
  "successful": true,                      // overall batch success
  "id": null,                              // overall id (usually null for batches)
  "items": [                               // one entry per submitted record
    {
      "successful": true,                  // per-record success
      "id": "001fj00001AjjqjAAB",          // SF Id when created
      "exception": null,                   // populated only on connector/SOAP fault
      "message": null,                     // top-level error msg if any
      "statusCode": null,                  // top-level status if any
      "payload": {                         // the actual SaveResult from SF
        "success": true,
        "id": "001fj00001AjjqjAAB",
        "errors": [                        // populated on SF business rejection
          { "statusCode": "INVALID_FIELD", "message": "BillingCountry: ...", "fields": ["BillingCountry"] }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

**Always read `payload.items[N]` — never `payload[N]` — for SF results.** A single-record create still returns `items: [...]` with one entry.

## 6. MUST Rules

- **One global config per org** (Sandbox vs Prod), reused across all flows.
- **Always set `type` attribute** on create/update/upsert/delete so the connector knows the SObject.
- **The `<sfdc:records>` payload MUST be a list `[{...}]`**, even for a single record. Wrap with `[ ... ]`.
- **Read results from `payload.items[N]`**, NOT `payload[N]`. See response shape above.
- **Treat `items[N].successful != true`** as a failure. Pull `items[N].payload.errors[0].statusCode` + `.message` + `.fields` for diagnostics.
- **NEVER hard-code credentials** in XML. Use `${...}` properties bound to env vars or secure-properties.
- **Test the connection** in ACB: open `global-configs.xml` → click the Salesforce config → "Test Connection".

## 7. User-Friendly Error Responses — MANDATORY pattern

Every flow that calls Salesforce MUST surface SF errors in a clean, actionable JSON shape — never dump raw connector payloads to API consumers. The agent MUST follow this exact pattern:

### Step 1 — In the SUB-FLOW, capture two variables before raising

```xml
<ee:transform doc:name="Capture Salesforce error">
  <ee:variables>
    <ee:set-variable variableName="sfErrorCode"><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/java
var item  = (payload.items default [])[0] default {}
var errs  = (item.payload.errors default [])
var first = if (sizeOf(errs) > 0) errs[0] else {}
---
(first.statusCode default item.statusCode default "SALESFORCE_REJECTED") as String]]></ee:set-variable>
    <ee:set-variable variableName="sfErrorMessage"><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/java
var item   = (payload.items default [])[0] default {}
var errs   = (item.payload.errors default [])
var first  = if (sizeOf(errs) > 0) errs[0] else {}
var fields = first.fields default []
var msg    = first.message default item.message default item.exception.detailMessage default "Salesforce rejected the request"
---
(if (sizeOf(fields) > 0) (msg ++ " (fields: " ++ (fields joinBy ", ") ++ ")") else msg) as String]]></ee:set-variable>
  </ee:variables>
</ee:transform>
<logger level="WARN" message="#['SFDC FAILED: ' ++ vars.sfErrorCode ++ ' - ' ++ vars.sfErrorMessage]"/>
<raise-error type="APP:SALESFORCE_ERROR" description="#[vars.sfErrorCode ++ ': ' ++ vars.sfErrorMessage]"/>
```

### Step 2 — In the OUTER error handler, map SF statusCode to HTTP status

```xml
<on-error-propagate type="APP:SALESFORCE_ERROR" doc:name="Salesforce rejected">
  <ee:transform doc:name="Map SF statusCode to HTTP">
    <ee:variables>
      <ee:set-variable variableName="errorCode">#[vars.sfErrorCode default "SALESFORCE_REJECTED"]</ee:set-variable>
      <ee:set-variable variableName="errorMessage">#[vars.sfErrorMessage default error.description]</ee:set-variable>
      <ee:set-variable variableName="httpStatus"><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/java
var c = vars.sfErrorCode default ""
---
(if (c == "INVALID_FIELD" or c == "REQUIRED_FIELD_MISSING" or c == "STRING_TOO_LONG" or c == "INVALID_DATE_FORMAT" or c == "INVALID_TYPE_ON_FIELD_IN_RECORD" or c == "MALFORMED_ID") 400
 else if (c == "DUPLICATE_VALUE" or c == "DUPLICATE_VALUE_DETECTED") 409
 else if (c == "REQUEST_LIMIT_EXCEEDED" or c == "STORAGE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED") 429
 else if (c == "INSUFFICIENT_ACCESS_OR_READONLY" or c == "INSUFFICIENT_ACCESS_ON_CROSS_REFERENCE_ENTITY") 403
 else 422) as Number]]></ee:set-variable>
    </ee:variables>
  </ee:transform>
</on-error-propagate>
```

### Result — what the API consumer sees

```json
// 400 — caller's input is malformed
{ "code": "INVALID_FIELD", "message": "BillingCountry: invalid country code 'XYZ' (fields: BillingCountry)" }

// 409 — uniqueness violated
{ "code": "DUPLICATE_VALUE", "message": "duplicate value found: ExternalId__c (fields: ExternalId__c)" }

// 422 — generic SF business rejection
{ "code": "FIELD_CUSTOM_VALIDATION_EXCEPTION", "message": "Account name must start with capital letter" }

// 503 — SF unreachable (handled by SALESFORCE:CONNECTIVITY handler, separate)
{ "code": "SALESFORCE_UNAVAILABLE", "message": "Connection refused" }
```

NEVER return:
- Raw connector payloads (no `items: [...]` in API responses)
- Generic strings like "Salesforce rejected the request" — always include the `statusCode` and the actual `message`
- Stack traces or `error.description` directly without unwrapping it through this pattern

## 8. SF statusCode → HTTP status mapping (canonical)

| SF statusCode | HTTP | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| `INVALID_FIELD` | 400 | Caller sent an unknown/invalid field value |
| `REQUIRED_FIELD_MISSING` | 400 | Required field not provided |
| `STRING_TOO_LONG` | 400 | Value exceeds field max length |
| `INVALID_DATE_FORMAT` | 400 | Date couldn't be parsed |
| `MALFORMED_ID` | 400 | SF Id format invalid |
| `DUPLICATE_VALUE` / `_DETECTED` | 409 | Unique constraint hit |
| `REQUEST_LIMIT_EXCEEDED` | 429 | Org API limit |
| `STORAGE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED` | 429 | Org storage limit |
| `INSUFFICIENT_ACCESS_OR_READONLY` | 403 | User lacks permission |
| `FIELD_CUSTOM_VALIDATION_EXCEPTION` | 422 | A validation rule fired |
| `INVALID_FIELD_FOR_INSERT_UPDATE` | 422 | Field exists but not writable here |
| anything else | 422 | Generic SF business rejection |

## 9. Inserting Salesforce Records — Reference Flow (uses the patterns above)

Validate input → transform to SF object → create → check `items[0].successful` → return id, OR capture SF error and raise with the user-friendly pattern from §7.

```xml
<flow name="accounts-create-flow">
  <http:listener config-ref="HTTP_Listener_config" path="/api/v1/accounts" allowedMethods="POST" doc:name="POST /accounts">
    <http:response statusCode="201"/>
    <http:error-response statusCode="#[vars.httpStatus default 500]">
      <http:body>#[output application/json --- { code: vars.errorCode, message: vars.errorMessage }]</http:body>
    </http:error-response>
  </http:listener>

  <ee:transform doc:name="Map to SF Account">
    <ee:message>
      <ee:set-payload><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/java
---
[{
  Name: payload.name default "",
  Industry: payload.industry default "Other",
  BillingCity: payload.city
}]
]]></ee:set-payload>
    </ee:message>
  </ee:transform>

  <sfdc:create config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config" type="Account" doc:name="Create Account"/>

  <choice doc:name="Check SF result">
    <when expression="#[((payload.items default [])[0].successful default false) == true]">
      <ee:transform doc:name="Build 201 response">
        <ee:message>
          <ee:set-payload><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/json
var item = (payload.items default [])[0] default {}
---
{ id: item.id default item.payload.id default "(no-id)", status: "created" }
]]></ee:set-payload>
        </ee:message>
      </ee:transform>
    </when>
    <otherwise>
      <!-- Capture using the §7 pattern -->
      <ee:transform doc:name="Capture SF error">
        <ee:variables>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="sfErrorCode"><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/java
var item  = (payload.items default [])[0] default {}
var errs  = (item.payload.errors default [])
var first = if (sizeOf(errs) > 0) errs[0] else {}
---
(first.statusCode default item.statusCode default "SALESFORCE_REJECTED") as String]]></ee:set-variable>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="sfErrorMessage"><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/java
var item   = (payload.items default [])[0] default {}
var errs   = (item.payload.errors default [])
var first  = if (sizeOf(errs) > 0) errs[0] else {}
var fields = first.fields default []
var msg    = first.message default item.message default item.exception.detailMessage default "Salesforce rejected the request"
---
(if (sizeOf(fields) > 0) (msg ++ " (fields: " ++ (fields joinBy ", ") ++ ")") else msg) as String]]></ee:set-variable>
        </ee:variables>
      </ee:transform>
      <raise-error type="APP:SALESFORCE_ERROR" description="#[vars.sfErrorCode ++ ': ' ++ vars.sfErrorMessage]"/>
    </otherwise>
  </choice>

  <error-handler>
    <on-error-propagate type="SALESFORCE:CONNECTIVITY">
      <ee:transform>
        <ee:variables>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="httpStatus">503</ee:set-variable>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="errorCode">#["SALESFORCE_UNAVAILABLE"]</ee:set-variable>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="errorMessage">#[error.description]</ee:set-variable>
        </ee:variables>
      </ee:transform>
    </on-error-propagate>
    <on-error-propagate type="APP:SALESFORCE_ERROR">
      <!-- Uses the §7 mapping (vars.sfErrorCode → HTTP) -->
      <ee:transform>
        <ee:variables>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="errorCode">#[vars.sfErrorCode default "SALESFORCE_REJECTED"]</ee:set-variable>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="errorMessage">#[vars.sfErrorMessage default error.description]</ee:set-variable>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="httpStatus"><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/java
var c = vars.sfErrorCode default ""
---
(if (c == "INVALID_FIELD" or c == "REQUIRED_FIELD_MISSING" or c == "STRING_TOO_LONG" or c == "MALFORMED_ID") 400
 else if (c == "DUPLICATE_VALUE" or c == "DUPLICATE_VALUE_DETECTED") 409
 else if (c == "REQUEST_LIMIT_EXCEEDED" or c == "STORAGE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED") 429
 else if (c == "INSUFFICIENT_ACCESS_OR_READONLY") 403
 else 422) as Number]]></ee:set-variable>
        </ee:variables>
      </ee:transform>
    </on-error-propagate>
    <on-error-propagate type="ANY">
      <ee:transform>
        <ee:variables>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="httpStatus">500</ee:set-variable>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="errorCode">#["INTERNAL_ERROR"]</ee:set-variable>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="errorMessage">#[error.description default "Unexpected error"]</ee:set-variable>
        </ee:variables>
      </ee:transform>
    </on-error-propagate>
  </error-handler>
</flow>
```

## 10. Common Errors

| Error type | Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| `SALESFORCE:INVALID_SESSION_ID` | Token expired | Connector auto-refreshes; if persists, check creds |
| `SALESFORCE:CONNECTIVITY` | Network / org down / wrong url | Verify Sandbox vs Prod URL |
| `INVALID_FIELD` in `errors[]` | Field name typo or invalid value | Check SObject in Salesforce Setup; surface via §7 pattern |
| `REQUIRED_FIELD_MISSING` | A required SObject field wasn't supplied | Add it in the DataWeave mapping |
| `DUPLICATE_VALUE` | Hit a unique constraint | Use `upsert` instead of `create` |
| Mule reports success but caller sees `SALESFORCE_REJECTED` | Reading `payload[0]` instead of `payload.items[0]` | Apply §6 + §7 patterns |

## 11. Local Testing

Mock the Salesforce connector in MUnit (see `mule-testing-munit.mdc`). For end-to-end, point the global config at a **Salesforce Developer Sandbox** — never test against Production.

```powershell
$body = @{ name = "Acme Inc"; industry = "Technology"; city = "London" } | ConvertTo-Json
Invoke-RestMethod -Uri "http://localhost:8081/api/v1/accounts" `
  -Method POST -Body $body -ContentType "application/json"
```
